		<dc:title id="title">The Nature of a Crime</dc:title>
		<meta property="file-as" refines="#title">Nature of a Crime, The</meta>
		<dc:subject id="subject-1">Epistolary fiction</dc:subject>
		<meta property="authority" refines="#subject-1">LCHS</meta>
		<meta property="term" refines="#subject-1">sh85044453</meta>
		<dc:subject id="subject-2">Man-woman relationships -- Fiction</dc:subject>
		<meta property="authority" refines="#subject-2">LCHS</meta>
		<meta property="term" refines="#subject-2">sh2008107175</meta>
		<dc:subject id="subject-3">Embezzlement -- Fiction</dc:subject>
		<meta property="authority" refines="#subject-3">LCHS</meta>
		<meta property="term" refines="#subject-3">sh2008119361</meta>
		<meta property="se:subject">Fiction</meta>
		<dc:description id="description">The unnamed narrator writes a series of letters to his lover, describing his internal struggles after having gambled away assets entrusted to him.</dc:description>
		<meta id="long-description" property="se:long-description" refines="#description">
			&lt;p&gt;The unnamed narrator is a lawyer responsible for looking after the assets of a wealthy family. He loses this wealth while gambling, but not all of it and still has hopes for recouping his losses. When his client announces that he is getting married and can take over the funds, the narrator is on the verge of suicide. He writes letters to his lover, explaining his predicament.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;The Nature of a Crime&lt;/i&gt;, first published in 1909, is the last of three collaborations between&lt;a href="https://standardebooks.org/ebooks/joseph-conrad"&gt;Joseph Conrad&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://standardebooks.org/ebooks/ford-madox-ford"&gt;Ford Madox Ford&lt;/a&gt;. A novella told in epistolary form, it remained out of print for many years and never received critical or commercial success. The book was rereleased in 1924, with new prefaces by the authors, written around two months before Conrad’s death.&lt;/p&gt;
		</meta>
